body.p:
We can recall that a number with an exponent of 1 equals the number itself;
	    for example, 

	    \begin{align*}
	    5^1=5.
	    \end{align*}

A number with an exponent of 2 would be that number multiplied by itself; 
	    for example,

	\begin{align*}
	    5^2 &= 5 \times 5\\
	        &= 25.
	\end{align*}

sidebar.p:
A square root of a number $@x$ is a number 
        $@y$, such that $@y^2 = @x$. The positive square 
        root of $@x$ is written as 

          \begin{align*}
        \sqrt{@x} = @y.
        \end{align*}

body.p:
However, it is important to remember that we could also square the value 
	   $-5$ to give 25, as

	     \begin{align*}
	     -5 \times -5 =25.
	     \end{align*}

Unless otherwise directed, we usually just consider the positive value of the root. 
	  When we need to consider both the positive and negative square root values, we can 
	  indicate this by using the $\pm$ symbol. For example,

	    \begin{align*}
	    \pm \sqrt{25} = \pm 5.
	    \end{align*}

We could write that 

	\begin{align*}
	    5^3 &= 5 \times 5 \times 5\\
	       &= 125.
	\end{align*}

And, an exponent of 4 would give

	\begin{align*}
	    5^4 &= 5 \times 5 \times 5 \times 5\\
	       &= 625.
	\end{align*}

Since 

        \begin{align*}
        5^3=125,
        \end{align*}

    then the third root of 125 will be a number that is cubed to give 125, 
    which we know is 5. We can write this as

        \begin{align*}
        \sqrt[3]{125}=5.
        \end{align*}

For our value, $5^4$, with an exponent of 4, since

        \begin{align*}
        5^4=125,
        \end{align*}

     the 4th root of 125 can be found by

        \begin{align*}
        \sqrt[4]{125}=5.
        \end{align*}

sidebar.p:
An $@n$th root, $@r$, of a quantity 
        $@z$ is a value such that

          \begin{align*}
          @z = @r^@n.
          \end{align*}

It is, therefore, the inverse function to raising a number to the 
         $@n$th exponent. The $@n$th root is denoted

           \begin{align*}
           @r = \sqrt[@n]{@z}.
           \end{align*}

answer.p:
We can remember that when finding the square root, we do not need to 
          write the value 2 within the square root. For example, 
          $\sqrt{4}$ is equivalent to 
          $\sqrt[2]{4}$. So, if we denote the root as $@r$, 
          then 

            \begin{align*}
            \sqrt[2]{4} = @r,
            \end{align*}

          which means that

            \begin{align*}
            @r \times @r = @r^2 = 4.
            \end{align*}

So, for which positive value of $@r$ will this hold true? 
          We remember that

            \begin{align*}
            2 \times 2 = 4.
            \end{align*}

Therefore, 

           \begin{align*}
           \sqrt{4}=2.
           \end{align*}

The $@n$th root, $@r$, of a quantity 
          $@z$ is a value such that

            \begin{align*}
             @z = @r^@n.
            \end{align*}

It is, therefore, the inverse function to raising a number to the 
           $@n$th exponent. The $@n$th root is denoted

             \begin{align*}
             @r = \sqrt[@n]{@z}.
             \end{align*}

Here, we are asked to find $\sqrt[4]{81}$; therefore, 
           we need to find the positive value of $@r$ such that

             \begin{align*}
             81 = @r^4.
             \end{align*}

We recall that

          \begin{align*}
          3^4 &=3 \times 3 \times 3 \times 3 \\
          &= 81.
          \end{align*}

Therefore, $@r=3$, and we can write

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[4]{81}=3.
              \end{align*}

We can evaluate the left side of this equation first, $\sqrt[3]{27}$.
          An $@n$th root, $@r$, of a quantity 
          $@z$ is a value such that

            \begin{align*}
            @z = @r^@n.
            \end{align*}

It is the inverse function to raising a number to the $@n$th 
            exponent. The $@n$th root is denoted

              \begin{align*}
              @r = \sqrt[@n]{@z}.
              \end{align*}

As we know that 

              \begin{align*}
              27=3^3,
              \end{align*}

           we can also say that

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[3]{27}=3.
              \end{align*}

It is important to note that the missing value in the question is not 
            simply 3. Instead, both sides of the equation must equal 3:

              \begin{align*}
              \underbrace{\sqrt[3]{27}}_{3} 
              = \underbrace{\sqrt{\nagwaTextBlank}}_{3}.
              \end{align*}

For the right-hand side of this equation to be equal to 3, 
            we need to find the missing value such that 

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt{\nagwaTextBlank}=3.
              \end{align*}

We recall that 

              \begin{align*}
              3 \times 3 = 9.
              \end{align*}

Therefore,

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt{9}=3.
              \end{align*}

Hence, the missing value is 9, and the completed equation is

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[3]{27}=\sqrt{9}.
              \end{align*}

An $@n$th root, $@r$, of a quantity 
            $@z$ is a value such that

              \begin{align*}
              @z = @r^@n.
              \end{align*}

It is the inverse function to raising a number to the $@n$th 
            exponent. The $@n$th root is denoted 

              \begin{align*}
              @r=\sqrt[@n]{@z}.
              \end{align*}

Since

               \begin{align*}
               2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 = 32,
               \end{align*}

             therefore

               \begin{align*}
               2^5 = 32.
               \end{align*}

This means that the 5th root of 32 is 2, so we can write 

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[5]{32}=2.
              \end{align*}

We can apply the same method to find the value of the next term, 
            $\sqrt[4]{625}$. We will need to find the positive value 
            of $@r$ such that 

              \begin{align*}
              625=@r^4.
              \end{align*}

We can establish that

              \begin{align*}
              3^4=81, \quad \text{@so } @r \neq 3.
              \end{align*}

Next, we can trial the next odd value, $@r=5$. This gives us

              \begin{align*}
              5^4=625, \quad \text{@so } @r = 5.
              \end{align*}

Therefore, 

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[4]{625}=5.
              \end{align*}

For the final term, $\sqrt{64}$, we can recall that since

              \begin{align*}
              8 \times 8 = 64,
              \end{align*}

           we can write that

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt{64}=8.
              \end{align*}

We can now substitute the values $\sqrt[5]{32}=2$, 
            $\sqrt[4]{625}=5$, and $\sqrt{64}=8$ 
            into the equation to find the value of $@x$, noting that 
            the term $\sqrt[4]{625}$ is being subtracted:

          \begin{align*}
          @x &=\sqrt[5]{32}-\sqrt[4]{625}+\sqrt{64}\\
          @x &= 2 - 5 + 8.
          \end{align*}

Simplifying this expression, we notice that there are terms that must be 
            added and subtracted. We apply the order of operations to simplify 
            this expression, giving us

              \begin{align*}
              @x=5.
              \end{align*}

body.p:
For example, is there a real value $@x$ for which 

	    \begin{align*}
	    \sqrt{-9} = @x?
	    \end{align*}

We know that we can square a positive and negative value in the following example:

	    \begin{align*}
	    3^2 = 9  \quad \text{@and}  \quad (-3)^2=9.
	    \end{align*}

We consider that

    \begin{align*}
        3^4 &=3 \times 3 \times 3 \times 3\\
            &= 81,
    \end{align*}

	and 

	 \begin{align*}
        \left(-3\right)^4 &=
        \underbrace{-3 \times -3}_{9} \times \underbrace{-3 \times -3}_{9}\\
            &= 81.
    \end{align*}

Therefore, if we consider the 4th root of $-81$, is it possible 
      to have a real value $@x$ for which 

        \begin{align*}
        @x^4=-81 \quad \text{@and} \quad \sqrt[4]{-81}=@x?
        \end{align*}

For example, are there any real values of $@x$ for which 

        \begin{align*}
        @x=\sqrt[3]{-8}?
        \end{align*}

We can calculate that

    \begin{align*}
        (-2)^3 &= -2 \times -2 \times -2\\
            &= -8.
    \end{align*}

Therefore, 

        \begin{align*}
        \sqrt[3]{-8}=-2.
        \end{align*}

Taking a different calculation, as we can evaluate 

        \begin{align*}
        \left(-3\right)^5=-243,
        \end{align*}

      we know that

        \begin{align*}
        \sqrt[5]{-243}=-3.
        \end{align*}

answer.p:
An $@n$th root, $@r$, of a quantity 
           $@z$ is a value such that

             \begin{align*}
             @z = @r^@n.
             \end{align*}

It is the inverse function to raising a number to the $@n$th 
            exponent. The $@n$th root is denoted

              \begin{align*}
              @r=\sqrt[@n]{@z}.
              \end{align*}

Taking the terms on the left side of the equation, we can evaluate 
            $\sqrt[6]{64}$ by considering which positive 
            value of $@r$ would give

              \begin{align*}
              64=@r^6.
              \end{align*}

As 

              \begin{align*}
              2^6=64, \quad \text{@wemusthave } @r=2,
              \end{align*}

          and, as such,

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[6]{64}=2.
              \end{align*}

Since 

              \begin{align*}
              81 = 9 \times 9,
              \end{align*}

            we can conclude that

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt{81}=9.
              \end{align*}

Since we have

               \begin{align*}
               3 \times 3 \times 3 = 3^3 = 27,
               \end{align*}

           we know that 

               \begin{align*}
               -3 \times -3 \times -3 = (-3)^3 = -27.
               \end{align*}

Therefore, 

              \begin{align*}
              \sqrt[3]{-27} = -3.
              \end{align*}

We can write that 

               \begin{align*}
               2^4=16.
               \end{align*}

Therefore, 

               \begin{align*}
               \sqrt[4]{16}=2.
               \end{align*}

We can now solve the equation 

              \begin{align*}
              @x = \sqrt[6]{64}+\sqrt{81}+\sqrt[3]{-27}-\sqrt[4]{16},
              \end{align*}

           by using the values $\sqrt[6]{64}=2$, 
            $\sqrt{81}=9$, $\sqrt[3]{-27} = -3$, 
            and $\sqrt[4]{16}=2$. Substituting these values 
            for the terms, and then simplifying, gives

          \begin{align*}
          @x &= \sqrt[6]{64}+\sqrt{81}+\sqrt[3]{-27}-\sqrt[4]{16}\\
          @x &= 2 + 9 + (-3) - 2\\
          @x &= 6.
          \end{align*}
